  "text": "The OpenJDK/JDK security provider registration framework consists of the following key components:\n\n## Base Provider Class\n**java.security.Provider** (src/java.base/share/classes/java/security/Provider.java) is the abstract base class representing a cryptographic service provider. It extends Properties and defines the putService() method (line 1221) used by all provider implementations to register cryptographic services.\n\n## Core Security Providers\n\n1. **SUN Provider** (src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/provider/Sun.java) - The core provider for basic security algorithms. It uses SunEntries (src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/provider/SunEntries.java) to define and register services including DSA signatures, SecureRandom, message digests (SHA-1, MD5), X.509 certificates, keystores (PKCS12, JKS, DKS), and PKIX CertPathValidator/Builder.\n\n2. **SunRsaSign Provider** (src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/rsa/SunRsaSign.java) - Provides RSA signature capabilities. It uses SunRsaSignEntries (src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/rsa/SunRsaSignEntries.java) to register RSA keyfactory, keypair generation, and RSA signature algorithms.\n\n3. **SunJCE Provider** (src/java.base/share/classes/com/sun/crypto/provider/SunJCE.java) - The cryptography provider implementing RSA encryption, DES, Triple DES, AES, Blowfish, ARCFOUR, RC2, PBE, Diffie-Hellman key agreement, HMAC algorithms, and JCEKS KeyStore. Services are registered via the putEntries() method using helper methods like ps() and psA().\n\n4. **SunJSSE Provider** (src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/ssl/SunJSSE.java) - Provides SSL/TLS support with KeyManagerFactory implementations (SunX509, NewSunX509), TrustManagerFactory implementations (SunX509, PKIX), SSLContext implementations (TLSv1, TLSv1.1, TLSv1.2, TLSv1.3, Default, and DTLS variants), and PKCS12 KeyStore. Services are registered via the registerAlgorithms() method.\n\n5. **SunEC Provider** (src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/ec/SunEC.java) - Provides elliptic curve cryptography including ECDSA signatures (SHA1, SHA224, SHA256, SHA384, SHA512, SHA3 variants), EC KeyFactory, XDH/X25519/X448 key exchange, EdDSA signatures (Ed25519, Ed448), and EC AlgorithmParameters.\n\n## Lazy-Loading Mechanism\n\n**ProviderConfig** (src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/jca/ProviderConfig.java) implements the lazy-loading mechanism for provider instantiation. The getProvider() method (line 152) contains a switch statement that maps provider names to their implementation classes:\n- \"SUN\", \"sun.security.provider.Sun\" → new sun.security.provider.Sun()\n- \"SunRsaSign\", \"sun.security.rsa.SunRsaSign\" → new sun.security.rsa.SunRsaSign()\n- \"SunJCE\", \"com.sun.crypto.provider.SunJCE\" → new com.sun.crypto.provider.SunJCE()\n- \"SunJSSE\" → new sun.security.ssl.SunJSSE()\n- \"SunEC\" → new sun.security.ec.SunEC()\nProviders are loaded only when first requested, avoiding unnecessary initialization.\n\n## Provider List Management\n\n**ProviderList** (src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/jca/ProviderList.java) manages the ordered list of providers. The fromSecurityProperties() method constructs the provider list from the java.security configuration file entries. ProviderConfig objects are wrapped in ProviderConfig instances, which handle lazy loading via the getProvider() method call when a service is actually needed.\n\n## Configuration\n\nThe providers are statically configured in src/java.base/share/conf/security/java.security. The file specifies provider preference order using the security.provider.<n> property format (lines 96-100), registering providers: SUN, SunRsaSign, SunEC, SunJSSE, and SunJCE. The Security class reads this configuration and initializes ProviderList at startup.\n\n## Registration Flow\n\nWhen a provider is instantiated, its constructor calls putService() (inherited from Provider) for each service it supports. Services are typically created as Provider.Service objects containing the service type (e.g., \"Signature\", \"Cipher\"), algorithm name, implementation class name, aliases, and attributes. The putService() method (Provider.java line 1221) manages a serviceMap and updates the provider's property strings for lookup."
